<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

  
<chapter xml:id="ch-intuitiveproofs">
  
  <title> Intuitive Proofs </title>
  
 <subsection>
    <title>What is Mathematics?  What is a proof?  Why do we prove things?</title>
    <p><em>What happens next? Does it always work? How many are there? Why does it work? What if we tried this instead?</em></p>
    <p>Questions such as these are at the heart of mathematics, where we seek to identify, understand, and explain patterns.</p>
  </subsection>


 
  <subsection>
    <title>Section 1.1 - Chessboard Problems</title>
    <p>My favorite parts of mathematics are ones that feel like games. The domino covering problem that you read about for today's class is one of them!</p>
    <p>Here's reminders of definitions and propositions from your text:</p>
    <definition>
      <statement>
        <p>A <term>perfect cover</term> of an <m>m\times n</m> board with <m>2\times 1</m> dominoes is an arrangement of those dominoes on the chessboard with no squares left uncovered, and no dominoes stacked or left hanging off the end.</p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <proposition>
      <statement>
        <p>There exists a perfect cover of an <m>8\times 8</m> chessboard.</p>
      </statement>
    </proposition>
    <p>Proof idea:</p>
    <proposition>
      <statement>
        <p>If one crosses out the top-left square of an <m>8\times 8</m> chessboard, the remaining squares cannot be perfectly covered by dominoes.</p>
      </statement>
    </proposition>
    <p>Proof idea:</p>
    <p>The author then proceeds to ask the following questions:</p>
    <ol>
      <li><p><term>Question 1:</term> If I remove two squares of different colors from an <m>8\times 8</m> chessboard, must the result have a perfect cover?</p></li>
      <li><p><term>Question 2:</term> If I remove four squares - two black, two white - from an <m>8\times 8</m> chessboard, must the result have a perfect cover?</p></li>
      <li><p><term>Question 3:</term> For every pair of positive integers <m>m</m> and <m>n</m>, does there exist a perfect cover of the <m>m\times n</m> chessboard by <m>2\times 1</m> dominoes?</p></li>
    </ol>
    <p>What are some other questions we could ask?</p>
    <activity workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>Explore one of the questions from the previous page with your team!</p>
      </statement>
    </activity>
    <activity>
